context: Energy production in Greece is dominated by the <a0_0><b5_0>Public Power Corporation<b5_0/><a0_0/> (known mostly by its acronym ΔΕΗ, or in English DEI). In 2009 DEI supplied for <a1_0><b6_0>85.6%<b6_0/><a1_0/> of all energy demand in Greece, while the number fell to 77.3% in 2010. Almost half (48%) of DEI's power output is generated using <a2_0><b7_0>lignite<b7_0/><a2_0/>, a drop from the 51.6% in 2009. Another 12% comes from Hydroelectric power plants and another <a3_0><b8_0>20%<b8_0/><a3_0/> from natural gas. Between 2009 and 2010, independent companies' energy production increased by <a4_0><b9_0>56%<b9_0/><a4_0/>, from 2,709 Gigawatt hour in 2009 to 4,232 GWh in 2010.
